<p><b>Biosemiotics</b> (from the <a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a> <i>bios</i> meaning "life" and <i>semeion</i> meaning "sign") is a growing field that studies the production, action and <a href="/wiki/Interpretation_(logic)" title="Interpretation (logic)">interpretation</a> of <a href="/wiki/Sign_(semiotics)" title="Sign (semiotics)">signs</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Biology" title="Biology">biological</a> realm. Biosemiotics attempts to integrate the findings of scientific biology and <a href="/wiki/Semiotics" title="Semiotics">semiotics</a>, representing a paradigmatic shift in the occidental scientific view of <a href="/wiki/Life" title="Life">life</a>, demonstrating that <a href="/wiki/Semiosis" title="Semiosis">semiosis</a> (sign process, including <a href="/wiki/Meaning" title="Meaning">meaning</a> and <a href="/wiki/Interpretation" title="Interpretation">interpretation</a>) is its imminent feature. The term "biosemiotic" was first used by <a href="/wiki/Friedrich_S._Rothschild" title="Friedrich S. Rothschild">Friedrich S. Rothschild</a> in 1962, but <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Sebeok" title="Thomas Sebeok">Thomas Sebeok</a> and <a href="/wiki/Thure_von_Uexk%C3%BCll" title="Thure von Uexküll">Thure von Uexküll</a> have done much to popularize the term and field.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since November 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></p>
